re 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n1282,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"A flexed budget adjusts the original budget to reflect the actual level of activity, providing a more accurate comparison of actual performance against budgeted figures. It is calculated by adjusting the budgeted figures based on the actual number of customers or units. A flexed budget is prepared at the same level of activity as the actual output. For example, for the month of May, a flexed budget would include calculations for food sales, drink sales, total revenue, variable costs (such as staff wages, food costs, drink costs, and energy costs), contribution, fixed costs (including manager's and chef's pay, rent, rates, and depreciation), and operating profit. This type of budget is updated in response to changes in the level of activity, ensuring that the budget remains relevant and accurate.\",7\n1737,\"\"\"REVENUE CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"REVENUE CALCULATION\"\" involves determining the total revenue by multiplying the number of customers (or quantity, Q) by the average revenue per customer (or price, P). For Cowly restaurant, the calculation is as follows: with 1,500 customers generating $75,000, the average revenue per customer is $50. When the number of customers increases to 1,800, the total revenue becomes $90,000 ($50 * 1,800). Additionally, revenue calculations at different price and quantity points are provided: at a price (P) of $250 and a quantity (Q) of 1,000, the revenue is $250,000 (1,000 * 250). At a price of $230 and a quantity of 1,100, the revenue is $253,000 (1,100 * 230).\",3\n757,\"\"\"MARKET SKIMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"Market skimming\"\" is a pricing strategy where an initially high price is set to maximize revenue from customers willing to pay more for the latest technology or unique products. This approach is particularly suitable for products with high development costs, short life cycles, and significant barriers to entry, which can deter competitors. The high initial price helps to 'skim' segments of the market willing to pay a premium before gradually lowering the price to attract more price-sensitive customers. This strategy is often used for breakthrough products or those that confer status. However, it is not suitable for objectives such as discouraging new entrants and shortening the initial period of the product life cycle, as in the case of Skulpt Co.\",4\n1729,\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\" is a pricing strategy where a low price is initially charged for a product, such as an anti-malaria drug, to make it accessible to a larger number of buyers. This approach aims for high sales volume to compensate for the lower price. By setting an initially low price, the strategy seeks to grow the customer base quickly, which helps to shorten the initial period of the product life cycle and reach the growth and maturity stages faster.\",5\n779,\"\"\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\"\"\",\"Price elasticity of demand (PED) measures the responsiveness of the quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price. It is calculated as the percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price. If demand is price elastic, a decrease in price will lead to an increase in revenue. A value greater than 1 indicates elastic demand, meaning demand is sensitive to price changes. In essence, PED is a measure of the degree of sensitivity of demand for a good to changes in the price of that good.\",5\n1731,\"\"\"PRICING STRATEGY AND DEMAND ELASTICITY ANALYSIS FOR SKULPT CO'S GSA PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"Skulpt Co is a manufacturer of electronic goods, specifically the GSA device. The company is analyzing pricing strategies and demand elasticity to optimize sales and market entry in new regions.\"\"\",4\n1727,\"\"\"ANTI-MALARIA DRUG\"\"\",\"TR Co's new and unique anti-malaria drug, which cost millions of dollars to develop and has obtained a patent, is expected to save millions of lives. There are no similar drugs currently available in the market, making this drug particularly significant. Although the demand levels are unknown, the launch is eagerly anticipated worldwide. The anti-malaria drug is also used as an example to illustrate the application of penetration pricing and market skimming pricing strategies, due to its unique characteristics and patented status, making it suitable for market skimming.\",3\n2196,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET PREPARATION FOR COWLY RESTAURANT\"\"\",\"\"\"Yumi Co's Cowly restaurant's budget preparation involves comparing actual performance against budgeted figures. The flexed budget adjusts the original budget based on the actual number of customers, providing a more accurate comparison of revenue and costs.\"\"\",1\n1483,\"\"\"QUIZ ON FLEXED BUDGETS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves statements about flexed budgets, which are prepared at the same level of activity as actual output.\"\"\",1\n1774,\"\"\"FOOD AND DRINK COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Food and drink cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $22,500/1,500 = $15 per customer; $15 * 1,800 = $27,000.\"\"\",1\n1775,\"\"\"STAFF COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Staff cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $31,500/1,500 = $21 per customer; $21 * 1,800 = $37,800.\"\"\",1\n1776,\"\"\"HEAT, LIGHT, AND POWER COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Heat, light, and power cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $7,500/1,500 = $5 per customer; $5 * 1,800 = $9,000.\"\"\",1\n1281,\"\"\"SENSITIVITY TO CHANGES IN DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the sensitivity of Product Tom to changes in demand, given its cost card and expected demand.\"\"\",1\n760,\"\"\"COMPLEMENTARY PRODUCT PRICING\"\"\",\"Complementary product pricing involves setting prices for products that are used together, such as printers and ink cartridges. The price of one product may be set low to drive demand for the complementary product, which is priced higher. However, this strategy is not suitable for Skulpt Co's objectives.\",2\n1721,\"\"\"STRATEGIC PRICING AND REVENUE OPTIMIZATION FOR ALG CO\u2019S NEW PRODUCT LAUNCH\"\"\",\"\"\"ALG Co is launching a new product with a three-year life expectancy. The company aims to set the right price to recover high development costs. Market research indicates that demand decreases by 2,000 units for every $2 increase in price and increases by 2,000 units for every $2 decrease. The demand curve is expressed as P = 310 - 0.001Q.\"\"\",3\n1723,\"\"\"REVENUE MAXIMIZATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue maximization occurs where marginal revenue equals zero. This is the point at which any additional unit sold would not increase total revenue.\"\"\",2\n1741,\"\"\"PRICE DISCRIMINATION BY PRODUCT VERSION\"\"\",\"\"\"Price discrimination by product version involves setting different prices for different versions of a product. Skulpt Co is following a price discrimination strategy based on location rather than product version.\"\"\",1\n1272,\"\"\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"PED = % change in quantity demanded/% change in price = [(2,600 \u2212 2,000)/2,000 * 100%]/[(40 \u2212 50)/50 * 100%] = 30%/20% = 1.50.\"\"\",1\n1273,\"\"\"QUIZ ON PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\"\"\",\"The \"\"QUIZ ON PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\"\" calculates and tests the price elasticity of demand for a product based on changes in price and quantity sold. It involves determining the elasticity by analyzing different prices and quantities sold, ensuring a comprehensive understanding of how price changes impact demand.\",1\n1267,\"\"\"MARKET SKIMMING PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKET SKIMMING PRICING\"\" is a pricing strategy where a high price is initially charged for a product, such as an anti-malaria drug, to maximize profits from early adopters who are willing to pay more. This approach is particularly effective for unique products with high development costs and significant barriers to entry. Over time, the price is gradually lowered to attract more price-sensitive customers. This strategy is also appropriate when the price sensitivity of demand is unknown, as it aims to maximize unit profit during the early stages of the product life cycle.\",2\n758,\"\"\"EXAMPLES OF BREAKTHROUGH PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Examples of breakthrough products include the car, penicillin, laptop computer, Windows operating system, ATM, and iPad. Breakthrough services include the Internet and online shopping.\"\"\",1\n1732,\"\"\"GSA\"\"\",\"\"\"The GSA is an electronic device produced by Skulpt Co. The company is considering a price reduction and analyzing the impact on demand and revenue.\"\"\",1\n1734,\"\"\"HAREKISH MARKET ENTRY\"\"\",\"\"\"Skulpt Co is planning to enter the Harekish market with its GSA product, aiming to set a minimum acceptable price to discourage new entrants and shorten the product life cycle to reach growth and maturity stages quickly.\"\"\",1\n1733,\"\"\"LOK CO\"\"\",\"\"\"LOK Co is a new customer that has placed a bespoke order for 5,000 units of the GSA, requiring additional production and packaging specifications.\"\"\",1\n1730,\"\"\"TR CO\"\"\",\"\"\"TR Co is a company that produces the anti-malaria drug and is considering different pricing strategies to maximize its market potential and recover high development costs.\"\"\",1\n1722,\"\"\"DEMAND CURVE FORMULA\"\"\",\"\"\"The demand curve formula used in the case: P = 310 - 0.001Q, where P is the price and Q is the quantity demanded.\"\"\",1\n1720,\"\"\"PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Penetration pricing involves setting a low initial price to attract a large number of buyers and gain a significant market share. This strategy is suitable when demand is highly elastic, economies of scale can be achieved, new entrants are discouraged, or the company wants to quickly move through the product life cycle stages.\"\"\",1\n1738,\"\"\"PROFIT-MAXIMIZING PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Profit is maximized when marginal revenue (MR) equals marginal cost (MC). The profit-maximizing price for the GSA is $252.\"\"\",1\n761,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF COMPLEMENTARY PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"An example of complementary products is printers and print cartridges. Printers are often sold at a low price, while the cartridges are sold at a high price to maximize profit margins.\"\"\",1\n1268,\"\"\"SELLING PRICE TO MAXIMIZE PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz on determining the selling price to maximize profit using the equation P = 60 - 0.01Q and total cost TC = 5,000 + 8Q. The selling price that maximizes profit is $34.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n1263,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"REVENUE CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue calculation is part of preparing a flexed budget for the Cowly restaurant.\"\"\",10\n623,\"\"\"MARKET SKIMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Market skimming is not suitable for Skulpt Co's objectives, whereas Market penetration pricing is.\"\"\",9\n636,\"\"\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"PRICING STRATEGY AND DEMAND ELASTICITY ANALYSIS FOR SKULPT CO'S GSA PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Pricing Strategy and Demand Elasticity Analysis for Skulpt Co's GSA Product involves analyzing the price elasticity of demand for the GSA device.\"\"\",9\n1607,\"\"\"ANTI-MALARIA DRUG\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Market penetration pricing is a recommended strategy for the launch of the anti-malaria drug to gain rapid acceptance in the marketplace.\"\"\",8\n1267,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET PREPARATION FOR COWLY RESTAURANT\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Flexed Budget Preparation for Cowly Restaurant involves the use of a flexed budget to compare actual performance against budgeted figures.\"\"\",8\n1262,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ ON FLEXED BUDGETS\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on flexed budgets involves statements about the characteristics of flexed budgets.\"\"\",8\n1264,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"FOOD AND DRINK COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Food and drink cost calculation is part of preparing a flexed budget for the Cowly restaurant.\"\"\",8\n1265,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"STAFF COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Staff cost calculation is part of preparing a flexed budget for the Cowly restaurant.\"\"\",8\n1266,\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"HEAT, LIGHT, AND POWER COST CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Heat, light, and power cost calculation is part of preparing a flexed budget for the Cowly restaurant.\"\"\",8\n1261,\"\"\"SENSITIVITY TO CHANGES IN DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"FLEXED BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"Both quizzes involve understanding how changes in activity levels affect financial outcomes, with the former focusing on demand sensitivity and the latter on budget adjustments.\"\"\",8\n637,\"\"\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"REVENUE CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Price elasticity of demand affects revenue calculation, as shown by the increase in revenue when the price is decreased from $250 to $230.\"\"\",8\n625,\"\"\"COMPLEMENTARY PRODUCT PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Complementary product pricing is not suitable for Skulpt Co's objectives, whereas Market penetration pricing is.\"\"\",7\n1609,\"\"\"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"PRICING STRATEGIES\"\"\",\"\"\"Market penetration pricing is one of the pricing strategies used to achieve specific business objectives.\"\"\",7\n621,\"\"\"MARKET SKIMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"STRATEGIC PRICING AND REVENUE OPTIMIZATION FOR ALG CO\u2019S NEW PRODUCT LAUNCH\"\"\",\"\"\"Market skimming is another s